3.1.2.2. Donor-acceptor chromophores
A second class of dye molecules that has received considerable attention for application in DSSCs and (bulk heterojunction) organic photovoltaics are the push-pull or donor-acceptor chromophores.
They typically consist of an electron-rich (donor) and an electron-deficient (acceptor) building block.
The large variety of both donor and acceptor units enables easy tuning of the optical and electrochemical properties through molecular design. Other advantages of this family of dyes in comparison with Ru-based metal complexes are the high molar extinction coefficients, lower production costs and a smaller environmental impact.234 The first report on the functionalization of BDD with donor-acceptor chromophores for photovoltaic applications was published in 2008 by K.P.
Loh and coworkers.138 Initial surface functionalization was performed via the electrochemical diazonium grafting of in situ diazotized 4-aminophenylboronic acid pinacol ester. Next, the donor- acceptor chromophore 2T-C60 was assembled on the surface in two steps (Figure 15a). First, the phenylboronic acid group was used to attach the bithiophene donor unit through Suzuki cross- coupling with 5'-iodo-[2,2'-bithiophene]-5-carbaldehyde (I-2T-CHO). Secondly, the acceptor unit was coupled to the carbaldehyde moiety by refluxing the diamond substrate, fullerene-C60 and N- methyglycine in toluene. It should be mentioned here that for donor-acceptor chromophores the organization of the dye on the surface plays an important role. After excitation of the chromophore,the generated charges will have the tendency to separate, where the electron and hole will move toward the electron-deficient (acceptor) and electron-rich (donor) building block, respectively.Hence, to minimize charge recombination, the donor unit should be as close as possible to the diamond electrode to ensure fast hole injection, while the acceptor unit should be in close proximity to the redox electrolyte. As a result, all donor-acceptor chromophores developed for sensitization of p-type photocathodes have a similar electrode-donor-acceptor structure. Photoelectrochemical measurements of the 2T-C60-functionalized diamond electrodes were performed in a 0.1 M Na2SO4/5 mM MV2+ electrolyte solution at an applied bias of -0.1 V. These proof-of-concept measurements resulted in stable light photocurrents of ca. 130 nA cm-2. The stability of this system was attributed to the strong carbon-carbon bonds at the diamond-chromophore interface and the robustness of the Page 23 of 53 Journal of Materials Chemistry C Journal of Materials Chemistry C Accepted Manuscript Published on 08 August 2019. Downloaded by Nottingham Trent University on 8/12/2019 1:55:05 PM.View Article Online
