3.1.2.3. Various chromophores
Apart from the metal complexes and donor-acceptor molecules, other types of chromophores have been employed as well to sensitize diamond electrodes. One such example is the polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon pyrene. A BDD electrode was first treated with singlet oxygen to hydroxylate the surface. The resulting alcohol groups were then employed to anchor pyrenebutyric acid molecules through esterification (Figure 19a).178 Photoelectrochemical measurements were performed in a 0.1 NaCl solution under illumination with a 351 nm Ar laser at an intensity of 5 mW cm-2 and a bias of -0.2 V. When an Ar-purged electrolyte solution was employed, photocurrents of 150 nA cm-2 were obtained. When the solution was saturated with oxygen, the photocurrents increased to 3.0 A cm-2, which was explained by the possibility of oxygen to react with excited pyrene molecules.
Other work involved the electrostatic self-assembly of phosphotungstic acid (PTA), a type of polyoxometalate, on BDD electrodes functionalized with a bilayer of an in situ diazotized pyridinium dye through electrochemical diazonium grafting (Figure 19b).142 In the action spectrum of diamond electrodes functionalized with only the pyridinium dye, photocurrents of approximately 600 nA cm-2 were detected at a wavelength of 350 nm and at an applied bias of -0.1 V. After self-assembly of PTA,the photocurrents remarkably decreased to only 50 nA cm-2 under similar operating conditions,indicating that the addition of PTA impedes the flow of electrons. Electrochemical analysis of the energy levels of PTA revealed that its redox potential is slightly below (0.3 eV) that of the redox couple MV2+/MV1+. As a result, the excited electrons from the HOMO of the dye are transferred back to the PTA layer, where recombination is higher since PTA cannot diffuse to the counter electrode.
