A limiting factor for high photocurrents on dye-sensitized electrodes, especially for diamond due to its intrinsic inertness, will always be the difficulty to anchor a large amount of chromophores. Lim et al. attempted to circumvent this problem by coating BDD with P3HT, a commonly employed polymer in organic photovoltaics.240 H-terminated, OH-terminated and O-terminated BDD electrodes were decorated with a thin (20 nm) layer of P3HT through spin-coating and the photovoltaic performance was compared to ITO. The lowest photocurrents  under 1 sun irradiation and no applied bias  were obtained for H-terminated diamond and the ITO reference (both ca. 3 A cm-2).
OH-terminated diamond electrodes on the other hand generated currents of 9 A cm-2, whereas the best results were obtained for O-terminated diamond electrodes, with photocurrents of 12 A cm-2.
The observed results can partially be explained by looking at the VOC for the different electrodes,which is defined by the energy difference between the Fermi level of the electrode and the redox potential of methyl viologen (Figure 20). H-terminated diamond and ITO both have a VOC of 100 mV,which is much smaller than the values (1.0 and 1.3 V) for OH- and O-terminated diamond,respectively. Additionally, in case of the OH- and O-terminated electrodes, an interfacial dipole with P3HT is present, which facilitates the injection of charge carriers, resulting in a higher photocurrent density. Under prolonged irradiation for 2 hours, no decrease in photocurrent was observed for O- terminated electrodes, which is in sharp contrast with the 52% decrease on ITO after only 20 minutes.
