30 The final system discussed here for photovoltaic applications is somewhat unique in the sense that not merely simple dye molecules, but more complex reaction centers are employed. These reaction centers are the biological units that enable solar energy harvesting in plants and bacteria.
Their highly efficient charge separation mechanism renders them attractive candidates for the development of bio-solar cells.241 However, great care is needed when immobilizing these reactions centers on inorganic electrodes to prevent their denaturation. Caterino et al. have successfully functionalized BDD electrodes with reaction centers via two different approaches (Figure 21).208 In the first strategy, a monolayer of 6-phosphonohexanoic acid was grafted onto OH- terminated diamond. The available carboxylic acid groups were then employed to anchor cytochrome c (cyt-c), an electron mediator that regenerates the reaction center, through an amide bond. Finally, the reaction centers were physisorbed onto the functionalized electrodes.
Photoelectrochemical measurements were performed in 10 mM PBS buffer with 10 M cyt-c and 100 M of free quinone molecule (Q0), which functions as a redox electrolyte (similar to MV2+ in the previously discussed systems). Upon irradiation with NIR light (870 nm) and at an applied bias of -0.1 V, this system afforded photocurrents of 50 nA cm-2. An improvement to this system was made by replacing cyt-c with aminomethylferrocene (AMF). The more efficient electron transfer between AMF and the diamond electrode resulted in 5 times larger photocurrents (250 nA cm-2) and a faster response to light/dark. A second functionalization strategy involved the polymerization of poly(tert- butyl methyl acrylate) brushes on the diamond surface.  Saponification of the methyl ester functional groups allowed attachment of AMF and physisorption of the reaction centers similar to the monolayer approach. Obviously, in this way a larger amount of reaction centers could be attached to the functional surface, which immediately translated itself in much higher photocurrents of 1500 nA cm-2. Despite the increasing distance from the reaction center to the electrode, the light/dark response did not decrease. Long-term stability measurements showed that after 15 hours of illumination, only 30% of the photocurrent was retained. This was attributed to a combination of denaturation and desorption of the reaction centers.
