3.2.1. NH3 synthesis
Another specific feature that is strongly related to the surface functionalization of diamond is the possibility to generate solvated electrons.242 This is a direct consequence of the NEA intrinsic to H- terminated diamond electrodes.243, 244 The terminal C-H bonds generate a surface dipole that lowers the electron affinity and thus increases the position of the conduction band minimum up to -1.3 eV (compared to the vacuum level).245 As a result, upon illumination of H-terminated diamond surfaces with UV light (hν > 5.5 eV), the electrons that are excited from the valence band to the conduction band can readily be ejected into vacuum or in a liquid in a barrier-free fashion.210, 246, 247 Through electron ejection into liquids, solvated electrons can be created. These solvated electrons are simple,yet, extremely potent reducing agents that can be employed in chemical and biological reactions.248- 250 In 2013, the group of R.J. Hamers was the first to demonstrate diamonds unique property to serve as a direct source of solvated electrons in water.242 The electron emission from diamond into water was detected by directly measuring the resulting solvated electrons employing transient absorption spectroscopy, as illustrated in Figure 22a. The diamond sample was illuminated using a pulsed UV laser (213 nm) while the change in intensity of a laser beam with a wavelength of 633 nm in parallel with the diamond surface was detected. In Figure 22b one can clearly see a decrease in intensity of the transmitted 633 nm light due to absorption by solvated electrons, which have a maximum lifetime of approximately 150 ns. By purging the aqueous solution for 90 seconds with N2O, a commonly known electron scavenger, both the intensity and lifetime of the solvated electrons drastically decreased. When performing this experiment under acidic conditions (pH = 2), barely any solvated electrons were detected since they rapidly react with protons to form neutral atomic hydrogen. When metallic electrodes (Niobium) are employed, the lifetime of the generated solvated electrons drastically decreased.251 This observation is easily explained by the presence of a continuum of states in metal surfaces, which provides an easy pathway for recombination. In diamond electrodes on the other hand, the energy of the solvated electrons lies well below the conduction band minimum and no or very limited states are available for recombination. The lifetime of solvated electrons near the diamond surface is therefore controlled by reactions with other chemical species. As mentioned above, these solvated electrons are extremely useful as they can be employed as strong reducing agents (ca. -4.6 V vs NHE) in chemical reactions that are not accessible through conventional methods.
