3.2.2. CO2 reduction
Apart from the photoreduction of nitrogen gas to ammonia, the photo- and electrochemical properties of diamond also make it a very suitable candidate for the reduction of carbon dioxide.
Nowadays, decreasing the amount of carbon dioxide in the Earth atmosphere is receiving a huge amount of attention, also at a political level, and large investments for the development of novel technologies are being made because of the impeding climate crisis. However, research on the photoelectrochemical reduction of CO2 in aqueous conditions has already been performed since the 70s.265 Depending on the employed electrode material, carbon dioxide can be transformed into a variety of valuable chemical compounds, such as methanol, formic acid, formaldehyde, carbon monoxide and methane.266, 267 Initial reports on the application of diamond electrodes for CO2 reduction solely rely on its electrochemical properties, i.e. a broad potential window. In these cases,highly doped diamond (B conc. 1021 cm-3) is either functionalized with Co-porphyrins to facilitate the Page 35 of 53 Journal of Materials Chemistry C Journal of Materials Chemistry C Accepted Manuscript Published on 08 August 2019. Downloaded by Nottingham Trent University on 8/12/2019 1:55:05 PM.
