3.2.3. Water Splitting
Amongst the different photocatalytic applications, the conversion of water to O2 and H2 gas might be the one with the highest environmental impact as this allows the conversion of solar energy into chemical fuel. In these photoelectrochemical cells, sunlight is absorbed by a semiconductor and the resulting electron-hole pairs can catalyze the splitting of water into its components. Depending on the employed photocatalyst, water is either oxidized or reduced in the respective oxygen or hydrogen evolution reaction at the working electrode. Generally, a broad absorption window, good charge separation and long term stability of the electrode material are required to obtain efficient electrodes for solar water splitting.276 Although diamond is not an ideal candidate as a photocatalyst for water splitting due to its wide bandgap, H-terminated detonation nanodiamond has been employed for the photocatalytic reduction of water.277 Nevertheless, the true potential of diamond for water splitting lies in its application as a protective coating due to its high corrosion resistance and transparency or as electrode material due to its good p-type conductivity upon doping with Page 37 of 53 Journal of Materials Chemistry C Journal of Materials Chemistry C Accepted Manuscript Published on 08 August 2019. Downloaded by Nottingham Trent University on 8/12/2019 1:55:05 PM.
