4. Conclusions and future perspectives
In order to transform diamond from a simply beautiful object to a relevant photoelectrochemical material, understanding and controlling the surface chemistry plays a crucial role. Diamond is generally considered to be a very inert material that is difficult to functionalize. However, after three decades of research on its surface chemistry, a multitude of innovative methods have been developed to alter the diamond surface composition and to attach functional (macro)molecules. The hydrogen termination on as-grown CVD diamond is readily exchanged for oxygen, nitrogen and even halogen atoms, drastically altering the surface properties. Depending on the treatment protocol or the applied potential during electrochemical oxidation, the ratio of alcohol, carbonyl and ether species can be controlled.32, 48 In most cases, OH-termination is desired as this enables straightforward further functionalization via silanization, esterification or thermal alkylation.
Similarly, for nitrogen-terminated surfaces a high amount of primary amine groups is targeted toward subsequent amidation reactions, which can be achieved by controlled plasma treatments.70 On the other hand, H-terminated surfaces have also been employed to covalently attach small (linker) molecules via stable and robust carbon-carbon bonds. This, however, remains limited to two well-known approaches, i.e. diazonium and photochemical grafting. Nevertheless, significant improvements have been achieved over the years for both grafting procedures. A major drawback of electrochemical diazonium grafting, the lack of control over the thickness of the grafted layer and multilayer formation, has been resolved. By either controlling the charge in a constant potential method, employing bulky diazonium salts, adding radical scavengers or using the spontaneous grafting method, thin monolayers can be obtained. Very recently, an alternative for the photochemical grafting of alkenes has also been proposed, that generates surface radicals, which can react with the terminal alkene functionalities.287 Accordingly, a broader range of molecules can be grafted to the surface since the prerequisite that they should not absorb light at 254 nm, as employed in photochemical grafting, no longer holds. Functionalization of diamond with molecules bearing reactive moieties via diazonium or photochemical grafting enabled the exploration of numerous chemical reactions on diamond. In this way, complex light-harvesting small molecule chromophores have been immobilized on the diamond surface toward the development of p-type dye-sensitized solar cells. Very important here is a good energy level alignment between the dye molecules and both the valence band of diamond and the reduction potential of the redox electrolyte. Hence, the surface has been decorated with various metal-complex, donor-acceptor and less conventional dyes such as polyoxometalates and biological reaction centers. Combined efforts on optimization of the employed chromophores and diamond surface chemistry resulted in the improvement of the photocurrent from a few nA to 6.5 A cm-2 for boron-doped nanocrystalline thin films and even 22 A cm-2 for boron-doped diamond foams.165,239 Additionally, the photoelectrochemical properties of diamond have been harnessed for the creation of solvated electrons, which are extremely potent reduction reagents that allow for the synthesis of ammonia from nitrogen and the reduction of carbon dioxide. Again, the surface functionalization plays a crucial role. Decorating diamond with protonated primary amines for instance increases the ammonia yield by a 3-fold.54 Similarly, embedding Ag nanoparticles in the diamond film or putting Page 40 of 53 Journal of Materials Chemistry C Journal of Materials Chemistry C Accepted Manuscript Published on 08 August 2019. Downloaded by Nottingham Trent University on 8/12/2019 1:55:05 PM.
View Article Online
DOI: 10.1039/C9TC03381E
41 them on top of the surface results in a more efficient reduction of carbon dioxide to carbon monoxide.259, 275 It should be mentioned here that in most cases the diamond surface functionalization has been limited to a single functional group, despite the existence of patterning methods and the availability of orthogonal functionalization strategies. For example by applying both photochemical grafting and thermal alkylation procedures on a partially oxidized surface, two different functionalities can readily be introduced. Even on a completely H-terminated surface, mixed layers can be prepared via diazonium grafting of different diazonium salts.144 This can afford significant advances in the solar cell field since dyes with a complementary absorption spectra can be attached. On the other hand, also biosensors can be developed that screen for multiple target molecules. Therefore, we believe that continued efforts in exploring and optimizing the diamond surface chemistry, with special emphasis on multifunctionalized surfaces, will pave the road to various applications of functional diamond substrates.


